Headline::::
'You could see this was big by the look on people's faces' – readers remember the Japan tsunami five years on




DateTime::::2016-03-11T01:00:19+0000



<p><strong>Yuuki, 26</strong></p>

<p>At 2.46pm on 11 March 2011:<strong> Student, Tokyo</strong></p>

<p>I was in Tokyo when the earthquake struck, midway through an information session that continued despite windows starting to shake and everyone hearing huge noises. People told us how safe the building was, but when we left , those from other floors had already escaped much earlier and were wearing helmets. <br/></p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/mar/10/the-faces-of-japans-tsunami-disaster-survivors-five-years-on">After Fukushima: faces from Japan's tsunami tragedy, five years on</a> </p>

<p>What was to come was the loneliest night of my life.</p>

<p>I remember seeing two office workers tackle eachother to get a taxi (probably because they were late for a meeting or something) as I walked to Tokyo station and there were many trying to buy as much as they could to stay overnight at their offices.<br/></p>

<p>At the time, I didn’t know the tsunami had already taken many lives. I saw a big explosion on a TV at the station, and it was the first time I realized that this was serious.</p>

<p>Twitter was the only way I could get more information, and I went to a hotel in Shinbashi which had become a shelter for the night. There were many people in the lobby already, sitting down on the floor and drinking hot tea. I found a spot and talked with people around me, looking on a map to make sure we knew where we were and whether any of us were able to walk home. <br/></p>

<p>After that, some people said one metro line had started up again, so I left the hotel to go to my university around 10pm – there were still many small earthquakes happening. At first, when I arrived, there were many students around so I felt relieved, but even here in Tokyo there were big cracks on the walls and I heard how some buildings were still dangerous. I was talking to friends on Twitter and one of them living near told me to come stay at her place, kindly. We watched TV news together and were shocked to see footage of the tsunami for the first time. We cried and couldn’t sleep at all. <br/></p>

<p>I still clearly remember when the sun rose and it felt safer somehow. <br/></p>

<p>Now: <strong>Film sales agent, Tokyo</strong></p>

<p>Two years later, I joined a government initiative called the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://sv2.jice.org/kizuna/e/what/about/">Kizuna project</a>, which sent 60 young people to the US for six months to pass on their experiences. We had many discussions, passing stories between us : some members had lost their houses because of tsunami, and a boy said some pigs had died in front of his house. </p>

<p>We organized events hoping to raise people’s awareness and to try to improve knowledge of how people can improve their safety in disasters. <br/></p>

<p> I got an internship at a Japanese film festival in Los Angeles, selecting films, and we showed a film about March 11th called <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2012/03/09/films/film-reviews/ridley-scott-wants-your-home-movies-for-crowd-sourced-311-tribute-doc/#.Vt8FA854X9J">Japan in a Day</a>, which had a strong message but quite a hopeful tone. Some members of the audience were crying and even the projectionist said he liked the film a lot: I thought my time in the US would have been worth it even just for organizing this screening.</p>

<p><strong>Jon Wilks</strong></p>

<p>Then:<strong> Editor, TimeOut Tokyo</strong></p>

<p> When the earthquake that triggered the tsunami struck, I dived under the desk and <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.digcontent.com/previous-publications/tohoku-earthquake-live-blog-shaking-building/">started live-blogging the experience</a>. <br/></p>

<p>My distinct memory of the earthquake itself was that it terrified my Japanese colleagues. They experience earthquakes all the time, but you could see how different this one was by the looks on their faces. All of their childhood earthquake training went out of the window. They just turned and ran outside. <br/></p>

<p>I also remember the first aftershock, within half an hour of the initial quake. I heard it coming: the earth audibly groaned and my Mac started sliding off the desk. We had what seemed like hundreds of aftershocks in the following weeks. I remember sleeping in the living room with the whole family. My kids slept between my wife and I so that we could lie over them the second a tremor hit, protecting them from anything that might collapse. <br/></p>

<p>We turned the online publication of the magazine away from entertainment (naturally) and for a month kept people up to date on how to help, which trains were working and how to deal with the craziness in the period afterwards.</p>

<p>Now:<strong> Content Strategist, Hampshire, UK</strong></p>

<p>My family and I moved from Tokyo to London when rumours began to surface that a child in a neighbouring school to my son’s was found to have traces of radiation in his urine. It didn’t seem worth taking the risk. <br/></p>

<p><strong>Yohei Koyama</strong></p>

<p>Then:<strong> Home in Shimogo-machi, Fukushima</strong><br/></p>

<p>I experienced the earthquake in my hometown of Shimogo-machi, Fukushima Prefecture. The quake alone was severe enough to make me feel panicked despite being quite used to earthquakes , but for me more traumatic was the nuclear accident. When I saw the explosion at the first reactor building , broadcast almost live in <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/environment/fukushima">Fukushima</a> on local TV, I remembered Hiroshima and Nagasaki. <br/></p>

<p> Because of the number of strong aftershocks that continued to occur for many months, things became traumatic. I experienced a strange sense of motion – as if always experiencing an earthquake when there isn’t one: it is called <em>jishin-yoi</em> (earthquake sickness) .</p>

<p>When I saw people fleeing the country on television, I felt alone and isolated. There was a severe petrol shortage in the aftermath and I couldn’t go anywhere. When my friends abroad insisted I should flee Fukushima, I was annoyed – how could I just flee, leaving my friends and family behind?</p>

<p>Now:<strong> <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.soas.ac.uk/staff/staff92184.php">PhD student</a>, London</strong></p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/mar/11/fukushima-daiichi-nuclear-reactors-decommission-cleanup-japan-tsunami-meltdown">Five years on, cleanup of Fukushima's reactors remains a distant goal</a> </p>

<p>So much has happened and so much has changed in Fukushima since 2011. Now television stations and newspapers report ‘today’s background radiation level’ of each municipality every day, and a number of radiological monitors show radiation levels in real time. <br/></p>

<p>Food produced in Fukushima is screened for radiation contamination and sold with a sign stating it has been “screened”. Also, people do talk about radiation – in fact some of them even make jokes. When invisible radiation is visualised and verbalised, it becomes a part of everyday life as well as a continual reminder of the presence of the nuclear crisis. I think many local residents still find themselves stuck in the midst of this, as if the time in Fukushima has been at a standstill since March 2011. <br/></p>

<p><strong>Ginny Takemori</strong></p>

<p>Then: <strong>Freelance literary translator, Tsukuba, Ibaraki</strong></p>

<p>I was working in my third-floor apartment in Tsukuba, a town 60km north-east of Tokyo. I spent the five minutes of intense shaking holding onto my computer monitor, unable to let go as my desk was pushing out from the wall into my stomach, and listening to things crashing to the floor in my kitchen. As soon as the shaking subsided enough to stand, I ran out of the apartment to find a lot of my neighbours already outside. I ran back upstairs to get my phone to find out details of the quake. We all assumed it was Tokyo, and were shocked to find out it was up north. <br/></p>

<p>Together we watched the building shaking and swaying in the subsequent aftershocks. One neighbour turned on her car radio, and we heard something about a tsunami – it said seven metres, and I remember looking up at the apartment, thinking: ‘about <em>that</em> height!’ My husband came back from work to check on me, and together we drove back to the university to help evacuate students, before driving through pitch black roads to my parents-in-law’s place to check on them. <br/></p>

<p>It was only then that I thought to check my email and saw panicked messages from all over the world. That was the first real inkling I had that it was a major disaster. We walked into the house about 9pm, and were totally shocked to see the images of the tsunami on TV. For the next week I accompanied my husband into the university to help out with translation material in the emergency room We were showering as soon as we returned home because of the radiation scare.<br/></p>

<p>My husband is a physicist and my father-in-law, now long retired, was an anti-seismic specialist in nuclear plant construction, so they were trying to get as much information on the situation in Fukushima as they could. I found it impossible to focus on my work when reality was far stranger than fiction, with strong aftershocks and the ongoing nuclear situation.</p>

<p>We first went up to <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/cities/2014/jan/27/ishinomaki-new-communities-tsunami-loss-japan">Ishinomaki, Miyagi prefecture</a>, at the end of June to volunteer, digging mud out of ditches. <br/></p>

<p>I remember the devastation was shocking. Cars, trucks, boats and even railway carriages were scattered everywhere, some jammed between or even inside houses. The stench was overpowering: silt flung up from the ocean floor, mixed with rotting fish and worse. The air was thick with swarms of black flies. Yet people were living here – fresh laundry hung on the balconies of damaged houses.</p>

<p>That year we like many made multiple trips, sometimes filling our car with fresh vegetables to distribute to people when we heard they hadn’t had anything fresh to eat since the disaster. We got to know many survivors , and have been recording their stories. We still go up as often as we can, and we keep in touch with many people there. I feel privileged to have come to know so many interesting brave people in Ishinomaki and Oshika Peninsula who I would never normally have had the opportunity to get to know.</p>

<p>Now:<strong> Freelance literary translator, still in Tsukuba</strong> </p>

<p>Normally I stop whatever I’m doing at 2.46pm on 11 March to light a candle and spend some time quietly remembering. This year I will be at an event in Tokyo, so the candle will be image on my phone, but I will still take a minute or so to reflect.</p>

<p><strong>Cody B</strong></p>

<p>Then: <strong>Yokosuka naval base</strong><br/></p>

<p>I was in Yokosuka when the earthquake first began, working a day shift watch at the naval base. When the shaking first began, we thought it would shortly end, but after about a minute we realized the intensity had increased. Everyone evacuated the building and went outside. I laid on a hillside for nearly five minutes as the ground shook, and I could see the buildings in town swaying violently. I was shocked that nothing collapsed in that time – Japanese infrastructure is very impressive. <br/></p>

<p>Once the quake stopped we tried to leave the base to see if there was anyone in town we could help, but they closed the facility – no one on or off except returning military.</p>

<p>We were ordered to our respective ships shortly after. As I approached ‘Destroyer Row’ on Yokosuka, I could tell the water levels were dropping in the harbor. All the mooring lines connecting the ships to shore were under intense stress. <br/></p>

<p>The tsunami warning came very quickly, and while nothing hit the greater Tokyo area, we knew that disaster had struck. Within two hours we were preparing to depart Yokosuka and immediately began a transit north in order to provide humanitarian relief. I can still remember the things and people that were littered on the surface of the water. While smoking a cigarette one evening, our ship passed by an entire home, completely intact, floating in the middle of open ocean. </p>

<p>Now: <strong>Cleveland, USA</strong></p>

<p>I no longer serve but get an annual screening due to the radiation emitted from Fukishima through the Veterans Association, but no illness has been noted as of yet. I pray for <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/japan">Japan</a> every day and I pray for the people we could not save.</p>

<p><strong>Basil, 29</strong></p>

<p>Then:<strong> Master’s student in Aramachi, Sendai</strong></p>

<p>My friends and I rushed to the doorway separating the bedroom and kitchen in my apartment and held on to each other until the earthquake subsided. It felt like an eternity passed before the shaking stopped.</p>

<p>By then the bowl of noodles I had made for lunch had been tossed to the ground in a fit of panic and the kitchen and living room transformed into a complete mess – with bookshelves face down on the floor and plates, cutlery and rubbish scattered around. The worst was over – so we thought.</p>

<p>Stepping outside brought us face to face with holes in streets that had swallowed cars, fissures and cracks running up and down what once seemed like the most solid and earthquake-resilient structures. <br/></p>

<p>The first idea that came to mind was to find a park, but to get to the nearest one meant going through crowded suburban areas surrounded by tall buildings. Instead we went to the banks of the Hirose river, a place I knew well. A few minutes after we arrived a large aftershock occurred – and dozens more were to follow.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/10/five-years-after-japans-tsunami-orphan-victims-lament-their-lost-parents">Five years after Japan's tsunami, orphan victims lament their lost parents</a> </p>

<p>Little did we know that by this time approximately 500 lives had been lost in my ward, Wakabayashi-ku. I was told later a raised highway had acted as an artificial levy, stopping the tsunami from making its way up to Aramachi and my apartment via the Hirose river, where we had initially sought safety. <br/></p>

<p>We wandered the streets for the next hour or so, before meeting my Japanese roommate back at my apartment. </p>

<p>The day seemed inert, as many of the shopkeepers and neighbours, many of whom were good friends of mine, littered the streets in silent congregation. Communications were down, but, recalling signs I had passed many times on my way to university, I decided to approach the nearest elementary school – a designated evacuation site via a packed convenience store where we managed to get hold of a large bag of rice crackers and a bottle of whiskey. There was already some panic about food shortages.</p>

<p>By the time night fell there were 3-400 people on the gym floor: we were told not to flush toilets as there was no running water, and volunteers organised themselves as we learned about a nearby Chinese restaurant that was dispensing plastic containers of rice for those willing to line up for some hot food – a rarity that did not go unappreciated. </p>

<p>I stayed in Sendai for about a week, then managed to leave for Niigata, and from there flew to Osaka and Naha, Okinawa, to stay with an old friend. In Okinawa I raised money for the victims by busking, donating to a special Japanese Red Cross fund.<em><br/></em></p>

<p>Now:<strong> Doctoral candidate and academic, Melbourne.</strong></p>

<p>The natural disaster and nuclear meltdown made me a more resilient and sympathetic human being. Instead of worrying solely about the well-being of friends and family, I began to pay more attention to various types of suffering that arise in extreme and trying circumstances.</p>

<p>I left Japan only a year or so after the earthquake and tsunami. </p>

<p><strong>Mutsumi Matsugu</strong></p>

<p>Then: <strong>With family in Tokyo </strong><br/></p>

<p>I was in my 14th floor apartment with my dad and dog in Tokyo. We went downstairs and evacuated to the grounds of a school in front of my home. We felt many earthquakes and aftershocks there, and I couldn’t call or email my family or co-workers to check on their safety for the next few hours.</p>

<p>Now:<strong> Children’s education business franchisee, California</strong></p>

<p>Like many small businesses we struggled after the earthquake, so I work in California now, and I worry about my family in Tokyo. I am afraid Tokyo will have an earthquake again in the near future, but it still has many tall buildings and is redeveloping for the Tokyo Olympics in 2020.</p>

<p>I wonder why the Japanese government does not say much about the radiation around Fukushima anymore. I think radiation will affect our country deeply. <br/></p>

<p><strong>Sam Keene</strong></p>

<p>Then:<strong> Teacher, Tokyo <br/></strong></p>

<p>The quake hit as we were preparing to dismiss the children at the British School where I worked in Tokyo. I taught nursery classes, so the children were only three. We had performed numerous drills throughout the year but still they amazed us with their fast response: the children went straight under the tables calmly and silently while my assistant and I stood in the doorframe.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/11/japan-fifth-anniversary-tsunami-nuclear-disaster">Japan marks fifth anniversary of tsunami and nuclear disaster</a> </p>

<p>The initial shake felt as though it would never stop. My assistant hugged me as we rocked and we sang Twinkle Twinkle Little Star to keep the children calm. Many of the parents were on the way and stuck in traffic, and gradually arrived to collect their children amid numerous aftershocks. We began getting accounts of what was unveiling further north: friends with families in the area became more and more anxious.</p>

<p>The last child in our school left at around 9.30pm – in our secondary school it was well after midnight. We walked home through the aftershocks. It was surreal walking along streets normally packed with traffic but now packed with people, shoulder to shoulder, picking their way home. <br/></p>

<p>In the following days we grew more and more scared. Eventually we decided to evacuate to Singapore. We arrived at the airport at 4.00am. There were thousands of people waiting to try to get on flights. We were lucky. We were ‘<em>gaijin</em>’ (foreigners) and thus had the freedom to leave. There was a large aftershock while we awaited our flight and we all just held hands. A lifelong nervous flyer, I have never been so grateful to leave terra firma. <br/></p>

<p>Life went back to normal in Tokyo. Our school reopened and we were called back to work. I had a very difficult time following my experience and could not settle back into my life in Japan. I eventually left to return to England at the end of the school year. <br/></p>

<p>Now:<strong> Department head, Milan</strong></p>

<p>I would still be living in Tokyo if it weren’t for the quake. I loved that city and have never felt so at home. I often think of my friends who lost whole extended families. </p>

<p>My partner and I will have a Japanese meal on the 11th as has become our tradition. I will contact the parents of the children in my class, many of whom I am still in contact with and send them my thoughts and hugs. <br/></p>

<p><strong>Michael King</strong></p>

<p>Then:<strong> Teacher on the JET program in Fukui</strong></p>

<p>The whole teachers’ room at the elementary school where I worked just stopped as we saw what was happening on live TV, and I then spent the afternoon figuring out how I could fundraise to take a truck up there.</p>

<p>I was based in Fukui, near Kyoto, working on the government’s JET program and running a volunteer group visiting kids in residential care, and my connections led me to Sendai about two weeks later. I drove up with a 2.5 tonne truck of supplies – and shortly after, moved there. My charity work became my full time job, focussing on raising money for child welfare institutions. <br/></p>

<p>The immediate aftermath was the most challenging for me, working with kids who had lost parents, and those in emergency shelters.</p>

<p>In a way being an outsider meant people could tell me things they were at times less comfortable sharing with others in the shelter. The most humbling encounter was with a 15-year-old who told me how lucky she was her mother and brother were able to be properly cremated, whereas so many other people had to buried to be disinterred at a later date. It was staggering how she could find a positive to hold on to.</p>

<p>Now: <strong>DPhil candidate, University of Oxford</strong></p>

<p>I have changed path and now study foster care in Japan, advising the ministry and politicians on current reforms to the child welfare act, and have been invited to meet and speak with the emperor and empress of Japan.</p>

<p>I plan to mark the 11th with some time to myself down by the sea. I have a lot of photos of the events so will probably look through these again.</p>

<p><strong><em>You can share your thoughts, memories and experiences in the comments below, wherever you were in the world on 11 March 2011. You can read more readers’ experiences and add yours at <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/56bb3259e4b084d24a9f07d1#contribute">GuardianWitness</a>.</em></strong><br/></p>




