Author::::usasoneiaswe
DateTime::::2016-03-11T04:08:21Z
My train was pulling in at the station before my stop, BANG. It was if someone had given us an almighty kick up the backside, the train slammed to a halt and rocked violently. The emergency breaking system certainly worked. Only yet half way a long the platform the conductor didn't want to open the doors, but we quickly persuaded him, once we were able to stand, to open those doors that were at safe to exit from. Still rocking, and difficult to walk I grabbed a steel strut that was one of many that held the roof up. It was rotating in a circle, it was an odd sensation, that which you view every day as solid, immovable, strong, moving as if made of rubber. On the phone already, I was speaking to my partner, who was under their desk at work, I could hear the smashes and bangs and wallops of things falling around them. First question, calm, almost normal: Where are the children? On the kindergarten bus by now? "Yes," came the answer. It was the longest wait to 3:15 ever, but arrive the bus did. That evening, with the power gone the silence and dark were a bizarre phenomena to observe in a city so usually blazing with neon. The toppled bicycle wheels gently spinning in the wind sounded like a storm. Then, well... The real fun began. Which way was the wind blowing? Time to get out. And so we left, taking one last look at a home we loved, believing that may well be the last we'd see of it. 



